Epicurus left three hundred volumina of philosophy, but his only extant writings are three letterS, none of them long, which give a summary account of points os his system 3 there are also many frag· ments. The work most akin to the poem of Lucr. was his treatise περὶ φύσεως in 37 volumina. It is known that he left two epitomes, a larger and a smaller, of his system3 and it is generally believed that the μεγάλη ἐπιτομή is the main authority. which Lucr. followed, though his own language here surely suggests that he browsed at large upon all the writings and extracted the matter of his poem from the whole field.

16-2 5. According to Epicurus, the universe (τὸ πᾶν) contains innumerable worlds (κόσμοι, mundz); between these worlds are spaces called μετακόσμια (intermundia), in which the gods live. Our world is bounded by the empyrean or upper air (aether); in this the stars are set, not worlds themselves, but forming quite small appendages to our world.

By his genius Epicurus was able to transcend the power of sight and discover what goes on outside our world3 and the same secret is revealed to all faithful Epicureans.
